Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: KenolKobil, Mumias, Sterling

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-09-22T16:07:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-22/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-kenolkobil-mumias-sterling.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell for a
fourth day, dropping 0.3 percent to 60.53 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi, the capital. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index declined for a second day, slipping 0.8 percent to
20,705.15 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a
statement on the bourse’s website. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  slid 3.1 percent to 775.59 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek. In Mauritius, the SEMDEX Index fell 0.3 percent to
1,886.56 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index advanced for the first time in a week,
gaining 0.4 percent to 1,114.56 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra,
after a public holiday yesterday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN), a fuel retailer with operations
in nine African countries, retreated for a second day, slipping
30 cents, or 2.9 percent, to 10 shillings. Oil fell to a one-
month low after the  Federal Reserve  cited “significant downside
risks” to the economy of the U.S., the world’s biggest crude
consuming nation. [bn:WBTKR=OANDO:NL]   Oando Plc (OANDO)  , a Nigerian  oil company , declined to
its lowest since December 2003, sliding 70 kobo, or 2.7 percent,
to 25.3 naira.  Mumias Sugar Co. (MSUG KN), Kenya’s biggest producer of the
sweetener, rose to the highest in more than six weeks, adding 10
cents, or 1.6 percent, to 6.55 shillings. Output of sugar in
Kenya, east Africa’s biggest economy, grew to 35,884 metric tons
on July from 33,495 tons a year earlier, Nairobi-based Kenya
National Bureau of Statistics said in an e-mailed statement
today.  Sterling Bank (STERLNBA)  Plc, a Nigerian lender, fell
for a second day, dropping 7 kobo, or 5 percent, to 1.34 naira.
Sterling will issue 3 billion shares for its acquisition of
Equitorial Trust Bank, a closely held bank, Reuters reported,
citing Yemi Odubiyi, chief strategist for the Lagos-based
lender.  To contact the reporter on this story:
